Price dynamics on travel since 1989
Until 1989, only five public tourist agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, tourism agencies at the time mainly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, Czech tourists traveled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Soci, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, which led to considerable restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The main paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual visits to socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovakian citizen wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation from that country was necessary; another individual travel was impossible.
At the time, tourist agencies offered to travel to the West, but they had to either stand up all night, with a sleeping bag, or have "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
A currency was required for travel to the West, and it was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not freely convertible; without a currency authorization it was impossible to obtain the money (western currency) to travel to the West.
Most of the Czechs have held their vacations at home, which has resulted in a large number of cottages and summer homes, and this practice remains today.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus survived the present revolution.
While before 1989, leave in GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs conducted 4.5 million leave in countries around the world.
The great paradox, which we no longer realize, is that by 1989 we could not freely visit Croatia at present because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa in the neighbouring countries of Western Europe was lifted, which led to a huge wave of short trips mainly in Vienna and Germany.
The Chechoslovakis couldn't take any trips to the West, they all wanted to go there for a while.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, since their income at the time did not catch up with the hotel or the pension.
A typical feature of Czech tourism during that period was the desire to bring their own food (conservations, salads, etc.) to save money.
Another important moment is the introduction of a freely converted Czech crown. After a decade, our tourists can finally freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income have grown, which has led to another important situation around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has enabled tourist agencies to prepare regular flights carried out by charter airlines, and compared to the past, airlines have now become incredibly cheap thanks to the ability to order discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all developed world countries except the United States, which made our travel even easier.
The next significant event in the history of post-revolution travel took place in 2000 and led to a historic first direct charter trip from the Czech Republic to the exotic country of Thailand.
Since then, direct charter trips have been carried by Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flight from the Czech Republic will take 12 exotic destinations.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs are visiting exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our post-revolution development, occurred in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States abolished the need for visas for Czech tourists, so our country has always joined the most developed countries in the world.
For the first time in history in 2008, Czechs spent more than half their vacation abroad (50.3 per cent); and for the first time in history they spent over 15,000 kroner per person during their vacation abroad, including their expenses in the destination paragraph.
